            <Control ISN_FATHER="7" _test_id="25" id="8">
              <PropertyList model="CTRL_GUI0_STATIC">
                <Text id="19" valUnicode="{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}{\f1\fswiss\fprq2\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}&#xD;&#xA;{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;\red128\green128\blue255;}&#xD;&#xA;{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 You can use \cf2 Gradients\cf1  to create interesting color effects for your users. These can be used on several different controls, such as Form backgrounds and static shapes.\par&#xD;&#xA;\par&#xD;&#xA;1. In\cf2  Options->Settings->Colors\cf1 , create a color to use as a gradient. The Foreground color will be used as one part of the gradient, and the Background color will be used for the other. You may use any color in the color table, but for future maintainability it is a good idea to reserve the color you will be using for gradients.\par&#xD;&#xA;\par&#xD;&#xA;2. In \cf2 Form\cf1  or \cf2 Control properties\cf1 , set the \cf2 Gradient Style\cf1  to something other than None.\par&#xD;&#xA;\par&#xD;&#xA;3. Set the \cf2 Gradient Color\cf1  property to use the desired color. You will see the effect immediately on the form, which makes it easy to judge the effect.\par&#xD;&#xA;\par&#xD;&#xA;\cf3\i\f1 Note:\cf1\i0\f0  Text that is set upon a gradient will look best if it has a transparent background. Data fields, on the other hand, look best if they are in a contrasting color (usually white).\par&#xD;&#xA;}&#xD;&#xA;"/>
